<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>09. "Mengel Wall closets, Closet Fronts, Sliding Doors." The Mengel Company; Louisville, KY; 1953.</strong><br />       <p>The earliest closets (from the Latin <em>clausum</em> for &lsquo;closed&rsquo;) were small, private rooms in the home used by the wealthy to enjoy books or art in solitude. Even the rich had few possessions prior to the 18th century so clothes and personal effects were most often stored in wardrobes, chests or clothespresses. It was around that time that closets, in roughly their modern, built-in form, began first appearing, though they were usually located near the fireplace and reserved for general storage.<sup><a href="3551#fn46" id="ref46">46</a></sup></p>
<p>Following World War II, largely in response to the increase in wealth and consumption that defined the postwar middle class, larger and deeper sized closets began to be built in new home construction. For the first time, most people had more stuff than they had space and henceforth storage in the home would forever be &ldquo;defined primarily as the need for the well-ordered accommodation of commodity excess.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3551#fn47" id="ref47">47</a></sup>  Furthermore, storage also began figuring into property values, with the Federal Housing Authority opining that &ldquo;provision for storage is a most important element in determining the desirability of the property to prospective purchasers.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3551#fn48" id="ref48">48</a></sup></p>


<br />
<p><sup id="fn46">46. Mary Miley Theobald, &ldquo;Myths That Should by Now Be History,&rdquo; http://www.history.org/Foundation/journal/Winter08/stuff.cfm <a href="3551#ref46" title="Jump back to footnote 46 in the text.">↩</a></p> 
<p><sup id="fn47">47. Diane Harris, <em>Little White Houses: How the Postwar Home Constructed Race in America</em> (Minneapolis : University of Minnesota Press, [2013]), 187.<a href="3551#ref47" title="Jump back to footnote 47 in the text.">↩</a></p> 
<p><sup id="fn48">48. Ibid.<a href="3551#ref48" title="Jump back to footnote 48 in the text.">↩</a></p><br /><br />
    	 "Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs," Case 7, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://digital-libraries.saic.edu/cdm/ref/collection/mqc/id/68837">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
